comment:
* Container of data passed to the {@link android.app.job.JobScheduler} fully encapsulating the * parameters required to schedule work against the calling application. These are constructed * using the {@link JobInfo.Builder}. * The goal here is to provide the scheduler with high-level semantics about the work you want to * accomplish. *

Prior to Android version {@link Build.VERSION_CODES#Q}, you had to specify at least one * constraint on the JobInfo object that you are creating. Otherwise, the builder would throw an * exception when building. From Android version {@link Build.VERSION_CODES#Q} and onwards, it is * valid to schedule jobs with no constraints.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_NONE
variables.comment: Default.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_ANY
variables.comment: This job requires network connectivity.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_UNMETERED
variables.comment: This job requires network connectivity that is unmetered.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_NOT_ROAMING
variables.comment: This job requires network connectivity that is not roaming.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_CELLULAR
variables.comment: This job requires network connectivity that is a cellular network.

variables.name: NETWORK_TYPE_METERED
variables.comment:
* This job requires metered connectivity such as most cellular data
     * networks.
     *
     * @deprecated Cellular networks may be unmetered, or Wi-Fi networks may be
     *             metered, so this isn't a good way of selecting a specific
     *             transport. Instead, use {@link #NETWORK_TYPE_CELLULAR} or
     *             {@link android.net.NetworkRequest.Builder#addTransportType(int)}
     *             if your job requires a specific network transport.

variables.name: NETWORK_BYTES_UNKNOWN
variables.comment: Sentinel value indicating that bytes are unknown.

variables.name: DEFAULT_INITIAL_BACKOFF_MILLIS
variables.comment: 30 seconds.

variables.name: MAX_BACKOFF_DELAY_MILLIS
variables.comment: 5 hours.

variables.name: BACKOFF_POLICY_LINEAR
variables.comment:
* Linearly back-off a failed job. See
     * {@link android.app.job.JobInfo.Builder#setBackoffCriteria(long, int)}
     * retry_time(current_time, num_failures) =
     *     current_time + initial_backoff_millis * num_failures, num_failures >= 1

variables.name: BACKOFF_POLICY_EXPONENTIAL
variables.comment:
* Exponentially back-off a failed job. See
     * {@link android.app.job.JobInfo.Builder#setBackoffCriteria(long, int)}
     *
     * retry_time(current_time, num_failures) =
     *     current_time + initial_backoff_millis * 2 ^ (num_failures - 1), num_failures >= 1

variables.name: MIN_PERIOD_MILLIS
variables.comment: 15 minutes

variables.name: MIN_FLEX_MILLIS
variables.comment: 5 minutes

variables.name: MIN_BACKOFF_MILLIS
variables.comment: 10 seconds

variables.name: DEFAULT_BACKOFF_POLICY
variables.comment:
* Default type of backoff.
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_DEFAULT
variables.comment:
* Default of {@link #getPriority}.
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_SYNC_EXPEDITED
variables.comment:
* Value of {@link #getPriority} for expedited syncs.
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_SYNC_INITIALIZATION
variables.comment:
* Value of {@link #getPriority} for first time initialization syncs.
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_BOUND_FOREGROUND_SERVICE
variables.comment:
* Value of {@link #getPriority} for a BFGS app (overrides the supplied
     * JobInfo priority if it is smaller).
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_FOREGROUND_APP
variables.comment: @hide For backward compatibility.

variables.name: PRIORITY_FOREGROUND_SERVICE
variables.comment:
* Value of {@link #getPriority} for a FG service app (overrides the supplied
     * JobInfo priority if it is smaller).
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_TOP_APP
variables.comment:
* Value of {@link #getPriority} for the current top app (overrides the supplied
     * JobInfo priority if it is smaller).
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_ADJ_OFTEN_RUNNING
variables.comment:
* Adjustment of {@link #getPriority} if the app has often (50% or more of the time)
     * been running jobs.
     * @hide

variables.name: PRIORITY_ADJ_ALWAYS_RUNNING
variables.comment:
* Adjustment of {@link #getPriority} if the app has always (90% or more of the time)
     * been running jobs.
     * @hide

variables.name: FLAG_WILL_BE_FOREGROUND
variables.comment:
* Indicates that the implementation of this job will be using * {@link JobService#startForeground(int, android.app.Notification)} to run * in the foreground. *

* When set, the internal scheduling of this job will ignore any background * network restrictions for the requesting app. Note that this flag alone * doesn't actually place your {@link JobService} in the foreground; you * still need to post the notification yourself. *

* To use this flag, the caller must hold the * {@link android.Manifest.permission#CONNECTIVITY_INTERNAL} permission. * * @hide

variables.name: FLAG_IMPORTANT_WHILE_FOREGROUND
variables.comment:
* Allows this job to run despite doze restrictions as long as the app is in the foreground
     * or on the temporary whitelist
     * @hide

variables.name: FLAG_PREFETCH
variables.comment: * @hide

variables.name: FLAG_EXEMPT_FROM_APP_STANDBY
variables.comment:
* This job needs to be exempted from the app standby throttling. Only the system (UID 1000)
     * can set it. Jobs with a time constrant must not have it.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: CONSTRAINT_FLAG_CHARGING
variables.comment: * @hide

variables.name: CONSTRAINT_FLAG_BATTERY_NOT_LOW
variables.comment: * @hide

variables.name: CONSTRAINT_FLAG_DEVICE_IDLE
variables.comment: * @hide

variables.name: CONSTRAINT_FLAG_STORAGE_NOT_LOW
variables.comment: * @hide

methods.name: public static final long getMinPeriodMillis()
methods.comment:
* Query the minimum interval allowed for periodic scheduled jobs.  Attempting
     * to declare a smaller period than this when scheduling a job will result in a
     * job that is still periodic, but will run with this effective period.
     *
     * @return The minimum available interval for scheduling periodic jobs, in milliseconds.

methods.name: public static final long getMinFlexMillis()
methods.comment:
* Query the minimum flex time allowed for periodic scheduled jobs.  Attempting
     * to declare a shorter flex time than this when scheduling such a job will
     * result in this amount as the effective flex time for the job.
     *
     * @return The minimum available flex time for scheduling periodic jobs, in milliseconds.
